Start minikube using Hyper-V driver (document example):
minikube start --driver=hyperv
minikube status


kubectl: use minikube’s kubectl or install separately
You can use the bundled kubectl via minikube:
minikube kubectl -- version --client


Create & verify an Nginx deployment (follow document)
Create deployment:
minikube kubectl -- create deployment mynginx --image=nginx
Verify deployment and pods:
minikube kubectl -- get deployments
minikube kubectl -- get pods
minikube kubectl -- describe deployment mynginx
You should see a pod with name like mynginx-<hash> in Running state.


Expose the deployment as a service (NodePort as in doc)
Expose:
minikube kubectl -- expose deployment mynginx --type=NodePort --port=80 --target-port=80
Check service:
minikube kubectl -- get svc
To get the service URL (minikube helps):
minikube service mynginx --url
Open the printed URL in your browser — you should see the default Nginx page.


Scale the deployment (as in doc)
Scale to 4 replicas:
minikube kubectl -- scale deployment mynginx --replicas=4
minikube kubectl -- get pods


Open Minikube Dashboard (optional)
Document recommends dashboard:
minikube dashboard
This opens the Kubernetes dashboard in a browser to inspect pods, deployments, services.


stop & cleanup (as in doc)
Delete deployment and service:
minikube kubectl -- delete deployment mynginx
minikube kubectl -- delete service mynginx
Stop minikube:
minikube stop
Delete the minikube cluster (if you want to remove VM/data):
minikube delete


Useful verification & troubleshooting commands (per document)
Get events (useful when pods fail):
minikube kubectl -- get events --sort-by=.metadata.creationTimestamp
Describe pods for details:
minikube kubectl -- describe pod <pod-name>
View logs:
minikube kubectl -- logs <pod-name>
minikube kubectl -- logs <pod-name> --previous
If Minikube fails to start:
minikube logs
minikube status











# verify virtualization
systeminfo

# enable Hyper-V (if needed) + reboot
Enable-WindowsOptionalFeature -Online -FeatureName Microsoft-Hyper-V -All

# download & install minikube
curl -LO https://storage.googleapis.com/minikube/releases/latest/minikube-installer.exe
.\minikube-installer.exe

# start minikube with Hyper-V
minikube start --driver=hyperv --memory=4096 --cpus=2

# use kubectl via minikube
minikube kubectl -- get pods -A

# create nginx deployment
minikube kubectl -- create deployment mynginx --image=nginx

# expose service
minikube kubectl -- expose deployment mynginx --type=NodePort --port=80 --target-port=80
minikube service mynginx --url

# scale
minikube kubectl -- scale deployment mynginx --replicas=4

# dashboard (optional)
minikube dashboard

# cleanup
minikube kubectl -- delete deployment mynginx
minikube kubectl -- delete service mynginx
minikube stop
minikube delete



You should see 4 mynginx pods. Verify load balancing by curling the service or refreshing the browser.
